{
  "text": "In conclusion, PEG coat is advantageous for drug delivery to the mitochondria, whereas covalent conjugation is highly effective for drug delivery to the nucleus (see Fig. 6 ). Previous mitochondrial targeting was achieved by highly positive charged (i.e., above 18 mV) nanodrugs [CITATION_1] . However, the observed electrical potential (1.19 mV) of PEG coat-DOX nanodrug in this study (Fig. 1b) was not on a comparable order of positive charges to attract mitochondria. Liposomal encapsulation was effective for drug delivery to both the nucleus and mitochondria (Figs 3g,h and 4 ), but not advantageous to drug selective for the nucleus or the mitochondria (see Figs 3-4 and 6) . The obtained results stressed the importance of choosing the appropriate type of nanodrug (i.e., liposomal encapsulation, PEG coat or covalent conjugation) for delivering organelle-specific active chemotherapeutic agents into the desired intracellular organelles.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "20878301"
